spanGrp.span: sa të se ktö' she-gẽ (hm) kabekar
when we go somewhere else and speak and people hear it is different,
je sa mĩ-gẽ-nẽ mãĩ kwãwã ra nã sa ktö'-gẽ-ra pe të í ksegẽ jaulë
se ktö' ka ka kser jie-wa ĩã
while some others like and wish to hear and learn it.
maleska-wa (_) je inga í kianã' bia jie-wa të í kse ĩã jie-wa të í ktö' guge
Some people do not like it
because they think that we are criticizing them when we speak it.
pe të í begetse-gẽ sa ktö'-gẽ-ra sa të jie-wa nẽ she-gẽ rö
That is why here in Costa Rica
those who of us speak our Cabecar language
mẽnẽ sa ktö'-gẽ se ktö'ye kabekar
look at it from a different perspective.
Siga-wa të maleska-wa të í she-gẽ-nã je rö böi
maleska-wa ĩã ra ka í denẽ böi
But the state has created many laws to help all those who speak a different language;
pero estee el estado të leye (hm) leye kreaba muchos ke je-wa të ka/ (hm) mẽnẽ se se ktö' (_) she diferente jie-wa (hm) jie-wa kimõ-glö jie-wa ayudaba-glö
therefore they have been able to succeed.
entonse je kueinga jie-wa an podido jie-wa jie-wa dögẽsau shkö-gẽ ñala böi wa
people realize that we are different
sa sũẽ-gẽ-nẽ sa rö jaulë asia otro
and our customs such as how they ate,
y jie-wa kostumbre-wa mẽnẽ sa yökö-gẽ
and made our houses long ago,
mẽnẽ mẽnẽ sa jũ yu-lë ñajiñara
that we do not sleep or hunt in the bush like them.
mẽnẽbi estee sa sa kupö-gẽ ka rö (hm) jie-wa bi kuna jamẽ mẽnẽbi jie-wa (hm) jie-wa mĩ-gẽ jirö ktö kã'yaka nã
They just ate from the bush,
Je bö nẽ kete-gẽ-ite rö jirö (hm)
they would not eat what the white sold;
ta ka jie-wa wã jirö tsõ watõ-nã jebi pe-wa kwãwã shtö ka kete
But nowadays our clans do not want to speak our language;
pero (hm) jira ka (hm) ka sa distsei-wa *të [wã] ka inga se ktö' bö sha-gle (_)
they want to speak other languages;
jie-wa jenã otro ktö' nẽ sha-gle
thus they like to play the smart alecs,
Je kueinga jie-wa (hm) jie-wa ñã ksö-gẽ
Jie-wa í she-nã je rö sisörö
jebi jebi sa sa ditsö rö
